  "text": "The Grafana unified alerting rule evaluation and notification pipeline follows this execution chain:\n\n**1. Rule Scheduler (schedule/schedule.go)**\n- `Run()` (line 175): Main entry point that starts the scheduler with a ticker\n- `schedulePeriodic()` (line 246): Main scheduler loop that processes ticks at the configured base interval\n- `processTick()` (line 276): Called on each tick, determines which rules are ready to run based on their evaluation intervals, creates rule routines, and schedules evaluations\n- `runJobFn()` (line 426): Called to schedule individual rule evaluations with optional jitter, sends evaluation signals to rule routines\n\n**2. Alert Rule Evaluation (schedule/alert_rule.go)**\n- `Eval()` (line 200): Sends evaluation request to the rule's evaluation channel (evalCh)\n- `Run()` (line 245): Main loop for individual alert rule that listens on evalCh for evaluation signals and processes them\n- `evaluate()` (line 392): Performs the actual rule evaluation, including:\n  - Building the rule evaluator from the evaluator factory\n  - Executing the query/condition evaluation\n  - Handling retries with exponential backoff\n  - Processing evaluation results via state manager\n  - Sending alerts to notification dispatcher\n\n**3. Rule Condition Evaluation (eval/eval.go)**\n- `Evaluate()` (line 97): Evaluates the condition by executing the query pipeline and converting response to Results\n- `EvaluateAlert()` (line 126): Converts query results to alert instances (eval.Results) based on condition logic\n- `conditionEvaluator.EvaluateRaw()` (line 59): Executes the data pipeline (queries/expressions) with context timeout handling\n\n**4. Alert State Transition (state/manager.go)**\n- `ProcessEvalResults()` (line 313): Core state management function that:\n  - Takes evaluation results and updates rule state cache\n  - Calls `setNextStateForRule()` to compute state transitions\n  - Handles NoData/Error state mappings\n  - Filters missing series to detect resolved alerts\n  - Calls `updateLastSentAt()` to determine which state transitions need sending\n  - Persists state changes via the state persister\n  - Records state transitions in historian\n  - Invokes the send callback with transitions needing notification\n\n**5. Notification Dispatch (sender/router.go & sender/sender.go)**\n- `AlertsRouter.Send()` (line 316): Routes alerts to appropriate destinations based on organization configuration:\n  - Determines if alerts go to internal notifier, external Alertmanager, or both\n  - Sends to internal notifier via `MultiOrgAlertmanager.AlertmanagerFor().PutAlerts()`\n  - Sends to external Alertmanager(s) via `ExternalAlertmanager.SendAlerts()`\n- `ExternalAlertmanager.SendAlerts()` (sender/sender.go): Queues alerts for delivery to configured external Alertmanager(s)\n\n**Key Integration Points:**\n- The scheduler wires everything via `newRuleFactory()` (schedule.go line 305) which creates alert rules with references to the state manager and alert sender\n- The alerting service is initialized in `ngalert.go` which instantiates and wires the scheduler, state manager, multi-org notifier, and alerts router\n- State transitions are the bridge between evaluation and notification - they represent changes in alert state that need to be communicated to notification receivers\n"
}

